07955nam a22011775i 9780228017851DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280178517 a10.1515/97802280178512doi  a(DE-B1597)658105  a(OCoLC)1371026831  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJF799b.C585 2023 7aPOL0530002bisacsh04a895.13422300aCitizens, Civil Society, and Activism under the EPRDF Regime in Ethiopia :bAn Analysis from Below /ced. by Logan Cochrane, Camille Louise Pellerin. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource :b7 figures, 3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in Protest, Power, and Resistance ;v600tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tAcknowledgements -- tCivil Society Activism under Authoritarian Rule: From Co-optation to Contestation -- tContesting the EPRDF Government: Mass Resistance, Political Mobilisation, and Legal Activism in the 1990s -- tAchievements and Resilience: Unspoken Stories of Civil Society Organisations in Ethiopia -- tEliminating Violence against Women in Ethiopia: Social Media Campaigns -- tEthiopia’s Women’s Development Army: A Moral and Political-Economic Perspective on Unpaid, State-Organised Rural Women’s Labour -- tThe Zone 9 Bloggers and Activism Collective: Civil Society and Online Activism in Addis Ababa -- tA Non-violent Struggle against the EPRDF’s Hegemony: The Case of the Muslim Protest (2011–15) -- tSpeaking Power to ‘Truth’: An Outsider’s Look into the Oromo Youth Resistance against the EPRDF -- tCivic Activism and Civil Society Reform in Ethiopia -- tBeyond the Public Silence: Civil Society Activism and Authoritarian Rule in Ethiopia -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 2014–15, the Ethiopian government, together with many academics and observers, was surprised by the outbreak of anti-government protests, as large-scale public contestation of the Ethiopian People’s Revolutionary Democratic Front (EPRDF) had been largely absent in the regime’s history. The dominant narrative about the EPRDF regime was that it was a top-down government, using authoritarian methods to ensure the population abided by its visions and directives, and describing its role in paternalistic ways, such as being the protector and guardian of the people.Changing this narrative, Citizens, Civil Society, and Activism under the EPRDF Regime in Ethiopia considers how citizens and civil society expressed their interests and exerted their agency in an authoritarian setting. Focusing on the EPRDF regime over a period of three decades up to 2019, the book explores civic activism in Ethiopia, presenting diverse examples of how citizens have (re)shaped the country. Challenging state-centric readings of state-society relations under EPRDF governance, this collection provides a counternarrative that emphasizes the role and agency of citizens and civil society. The contributing authors draw on a heuristic analytical framework that examines different types of interactions between civil society and state actors (co-optation, co-operation, coexistence, and contestation) and captures the ways in which civil society actors make their voices heard.At a time when authoritarian forms of governance are increasingly prevalent across the world, this critically important collection offers insight into how citizens claim their agency and challenge state power in apparently top-down contexts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivil societyzEthiopiavCase studies. 0aPolitical activistszEthiopia. 0aPolitical participationzEthiopiavCase studies. 0aPol